                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "C726b",
                  "name": "H1",
                  "fill": "$--foreground",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "The double-charge bug, and why idempotency keys aren't optional.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.08,
                  "fontFamily": "$--font-sans",
                  "fontSize": 46,
                  "fontWeight": "600",
                  "letterSpacing": -1.8
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "Pc2qN",
                  "name": "S1",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 18
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "ctbsS",
                  "name": "Problem",
                  "fill": "$--muted-foreground",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "A retry or a crash turns one payment into two, and your customer notices before you do.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.5,
                  "fontFamily": "$--font-sans",
                  "fontSize": 21,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "NbOy8",
                  "name": "S2",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 16
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "fPd03",
                  "name": "Meta",
                  "gap": 10,
                  "alignItems": "center",
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "g5uM3n",
                      "name": "M",
                      "fill": "$--subtle-foreground",
                      "content": "6 min read  ·  Updated Jul 2026",
                      "fontFamily": "$--font-mono",
                      "fontSize": 12.5,
                      "fontWeight": "normal"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "RuXPR",
                  "name": "S3",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 48
                },
                {
                  "id": "eCJmp",
                  "type": "ref",
                  "ref": "vf0Be",
                  "name": "01 · The scenario",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "descendants": {
                    "HNRFO": {
                      "content": "01 · THE SCENARIO"
                    },
                    "OV28Z": {
                      "content": "It's the 1st. Your billing job wakes up and starts charging the subscriptions that are due. Two-thirds of the way through, the process is killed: a deploy, an out-of-memory, a dropped connection. It restarts and picks the run back up. Some of those subscriptions were already charged. A customer gets debited twice for the same month."
                    }
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "b7oM8I",
                  "name": "BS",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 40
                },
                {
                  "id": "jTOsE",
                  "type": "ref",
                  "ref": "vf0Be",
                  "name": "02 · The naive approach",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "descendants": {
                    "HNRFO": {
                      "content": "02 · THE NAIVE APPROACH"
                    },
                    "OV28Z": {
                      "content": "Loop over due subscriptions, call the charge API for each, mark it paid in your database. It works perfectly in every test, because tests don't get killed halfway through."
                    }
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "xnBl4",
                  "name": "BS",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 40
                },
                {
                  "id": "YTaYZ",
                  "type": "ref",
                  "ref": "vf0Be",
                  "name": "03 · Why it breaks",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "descendants": {
                    "HNRFO": {
                      "content": "03 · WHY IT BREAKS"
                    },
                    "OV28Z": {
                      "content": "The charge and the mark-as-paid write aren't one atomic thing, and the process isn't guaranteed to finish. On restart you can't tell already-charged from never-charged, so you re-charge. Where balances are thin, a surprise double-debit isn't just a refund. It's a support ticket, a chargeback, and a customer who now distrusts every future charge. One bad run can do this to thousands of subscriptions at once."
                    }
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "XH4os",
                  "name": "BS",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 40
                },
                {
                  "id": "WHKYV",
                  "type": "ref",
                  "ref": "vf0Be",
                  "name": "beat4",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "descendants": {
                    "HNRFO": {
                      "content": "04 · HOW NOMBA ONE HANDLES IT"
                    },
                    "OV28Z": {
                      "content": "Every charge attempt carries a stable idempotency reference derived from the subscription and the billing period. A unique constraint on (subscription, period) makes a duplicate invoice structurally impossible, and the reference tells the rail this is the same attempt, not a new one. Kill the job anywhere and restart it. It resolves to exactly one charge and one ledger entry, every time. The database makes the double-charge impossible; it isn't guarded by hopeful code."
                    }
                  }
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "ataFs",
                  "name": "CS",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 20
                },
